{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}} {{Infobox film |name=GTFO |image=GTFO (film) Promo.png |director=Shannon Sun-Higginson |producer=Shannon Sun-Higginson |starring={{startplainlist}} * [[Anita Sarkeesian]] * [[Leigh Alexander (journalist)|Leigh Alexander]] * [[Brenda Romero]] * [[Robin Hunicke]] * [[Rhianna Pratchett]] {{endplainlist}} |country=United States |released={{Film date|2015|03|14|SXSW}} |language=English |runtime=76 minutes }}
'''''GTFO''''' (also known as '''''GTFO: Get the F&#% Out''''') is a 2015 American documentary film,<ref>{{cite web|author=<!-- Staff writer, no by-line -->|work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|title=15 Must-See Movies at SXSW Film Festival 2015|date=March 9, 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/15-must-see-movies-at-sxsw-film-festival-2015-20150309/gtfo-get-the-f-out-20150309|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> directed by Shannon Sun-Higginson, about [[Sexism in video gaming|sexism]] and [[Women and video games|women in the world of video games]].<ref name=NYT /><ref name=LATimes>{{cite web|last=Martens|first=Todd|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/games/female-gamers-tell-their-stories-in-gtfo-which-tackles-sexism-in-gaming-industry/|title=SXSW: Female gamers tell their stories in ‘GTFO,’ which tackles industry sexism|date=March 13, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=March 16, 2015}}</ref> It premiered at [[South by Southwest]] on March 14, 2015.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=In the Documentary ‘GTFO,’ Female Video Gamers Fight Back|first=Robert|last=Ito|date=March 6, 2015|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/08/movies/in-the-documentary-gtfo-female-video-gamers-fight-back.html?|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>
Sun-Higginson, a documentary filmmaker from New York City,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shannonsun.com/about.html |title=ABOUT |work=Shannon Sun-Higginson |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150521115542/http://www.shannonsun.com/about.html |archivedate=May 21, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> began work on ''GTFO'' in early 2012 and ultimately funded it as a [[Kickstarter]] project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/shannonsun/gtfo|title=GTFO: A Film About Women in Gaming|work=Kickstarter}}</ref> She was initially inspired to create the film after watching a clip from live-stream gaming competition Cross Assault in which a player repeatedly sexually harassed his teammate.<ref name="NYT" /> Sun-Higginson then "decided to take a step back and explore what it means to be a woman in gaming in general, both the positive and the negative."<ref name="NYT" />
The movie compiles interviews from gamers, developers, journalists to show how pervasive sexist behavior is in the gaming world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/culture/2015/06/18/docfest-film-reviews-playing-games-with-top-spin-and-gtfo/|title=DocFest film reviews: Playing games with ‘Top Spin’ and ‘GTFO’|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|first=John|last=Angelico|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref>
The film's premiere at South by Southwest was met with primarily favorable reviews, with critic Dennis Harvey commenting: "Several other documentaries are currently in the works on the same subject, and many will no doubt be a lot slicker than 'GTFO.' But the rough edges of Sun-Higginson’s Kickstarter-funded feature lend it an ingratiating, unpretentious modesty, and its lack of rancor on a topic that might’ve easily supported a more sensationalist approach can only be a plus in reaching male gamers most in need of its wake-up call."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/sxsw-film-review-gtfo-get-the-f-out-1201458625/|title=‘GTFO’ Review: An Entertaining, Accessible Look at Misogyny in the Videogaming World - Variety|author=Dennis Harvey|work=Variety}}</ref>
